  "body": "## Issue\r\nOn Linux backslashes (`\\`) can be freely used in file names and are valid characters. Truffle, however, normalizes them into forward slashes. When both a name with a backslash (`a\\b.sol`) and a file in a subdirectory (`a/b.sol`) are present, Truffle chooses the former and silently ignores the latter.\r\n\r\nI think that Truffle should either include both files in the input or report an error when it encounters such a situation.\r\n\r\n## Steps to Reproduce\r\n```bash\r\nmkdir truffle-test/\r\ncd truffle-test/\r\nnpm install truffle\r\nnpx truffle init\r\necho 'module.exports.compilers.solc.version = \"0.8.6\";' >> truffle-config.js\r\n\r\nmkdir contracts/c/\r\necho 'contract C1 {}' > contracts/c/C.sol\r\necho 'contract C2 {}' > contracts/c\\\\C.sol\r\nnpx truffle compile\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Actual Results\r\n```\r\n> Artifacts written to /tmp/truffle-test/build/contracts\r\n> Compiled successfully using:\r\n   - solc: 0.8.6+commit.11564f7e.Emscripten.clang\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe `sources` dict in the JSON input contains these entries:\r\n```json\r\n\"project:/contracts/c/C.sol\": { \"content\": \"contract C2 {}\\n\" }\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Expected Behavior\r\nBoth contracts should be available and stored under the correct names:\r\n```json\r\n\"project:/contracts/c/C.sol\": { \"content\": \"contract C1 {}\\n\" },\r\n\"project:/contracts/c\\\\C.sol\": { \"content\": \"contract C2 {}\\n\" }\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Environment\r\n* Operating System: Arch Linux\r\n* Truffle version: both `5.3.14` and current `develop` (abfb3646eea9d57e0a6f9186c12bb51680c181d8)\r\n* node version: `v16.4.2`\r\n* npm version: `7.17.0`",
